oc:kn_54ece0f3 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When determining hierarchy depth for a site" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Go as flat as possible while keeping navigation clean. If a nav dropdown has 20+ items, add a level of hierarchy. Most sites should target 2-3 levels of depth." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Flat architectures improve crawlability and user findability, but excessive flatness creates navigation bloat. Balance depth with navigability." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_79c06289 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When defining URL patterns for any page type" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use human-readable, hyphen-separated, lowercase URLs that reflect the hierarchy: /features/analytics not /f/a123. Use slugs, not IDs. Keep URLs short but descriptive." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Readable URLs improve click-through rates in search results, are easier to share, and provide both users and search engines with navigation context." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_8b223833 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When restructuring URLs or defining URL patterns" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never change URLs without implementing 301 redirects from old to new. Never use dates in blog URLs, IDs instead of slugs, underscores instead of hyphens, or query parameters for content pages." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Changing URLs without redirects loses backlink equity and creates broken links. Dates in URLs add unnecessary length and make content feel dated. IDs are not human-readable." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_91977178 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When producing final site architecture deliverables" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Deliverables for a complete site architecture plan: 1) Page Hierarchy (ASCII tree with URLs), 2) Visual Sitemap (Mermaid graph TD with nav zones), 3) URL Map Table (Page, URL, Parent, Nav Location, Priority), 4) Navigation Spec (header, footer, sidebar, breadcrumbs), 5) Internal Linking Plan (hubs, spokes, cross-section links, orphan audit)" ;
    oc:hasRationale "A structured output ensures all architectural dimensions are addressed and the plan is actionable for designers, developers, and content teams." .

oc:kn_9e6210cb a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before beginning any site architecture planning" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for product-marketing-context.md before asking questions. Gather business context (company purpose, audiences, goals), current state (new vs restructuring), site type, and content inventory before designing architecture." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Architecture decisions depend on business goals, audience needs, and existing constraints. Without context, the plan won't align with real requirements." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_9f846b17 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing internal linking for blog, resource, or programmatic SEO sections" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For content-heavy sites, organize around hub-and-spoke model: hub page links to all spokes, each spoke links back to hub, spokes link to each other where relevant." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Hub-and-spoke concentrates authority on pillar pages, creates dense internal link networks, and helps search engines understand topical relationships." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_ab367a46 a oc:AmbiguityTolerance,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When user requests overlap with technical SEO or schema markup tasks" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Recognize boundary with technical SEO: site-architecture handles page hierarchy, navigation, and URL structure design. XML sitemaps, crawl errors, and indexation belong to seo-audit. Structured data belongs to schema-markup." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Clear skill boundaries prevent duplicate work and ensure the right expertise is applied. Architecture is design; technical SEO is implementation and diagnostics." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_d9f3d45c a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When planning internal linking strategy" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Every page must have at least one internal link pointing to it (no orphan pages). Use descriptive anchor text — never 'click here' or 'read more'." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Orphan pages are invisible to search engines and unreachable by users. Descriptive anchors provide SEO value and user context." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_da45d3e3 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating or designing page hierarchy depth" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Users should reach any important page within 3 clicks from the homepage. If critical pages are buried 4+ levels deep, restructure the hierarchy." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The 3-click rule is a usability heuristic — not absolute, but deep nesting signals architectural problems and poor user experience." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_fbf26f23 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing header navigation for any site type" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Limit primary header navigation to 4-7 items maximum. More items cause decision paralysis and poor mobile experience." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Hick's Law: more choices increase decision time. Users scan nav quickly; too many options reduce findability." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

